title.narrative: OUTPUT 2: INTEGRATED NEWBORN AND CHILD-HEALTH INTERVENTIONS

description.narrative: By 2022, children under 5 years, their mothers and adolescents in targeted districts and high-risk urban areas have access to integrated MNCAH and immunization services in emergency and non-emergency situations., which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, the most at-risk newborns and children are benefiting from integrated newborn, child health interventions and healthy behaviours.

description.narrative: Access to quality health services was improved, including vaccination through cold chain upgrades, the birth dose initiative (reaching 70,000 children) and training and resources to health care providers ensuring management of 2 million children for pneumonia and diarrhoea. In Larkana, 98 per cent of people registered as living with HIV were provided anti-retroviral treatment. UNICEF contributed to updated guidelines on managing COVID-19 in children and provided PPE to healthcare workers to limit its spread. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:29/12/2021
